{"actual_usd":0.156725,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":229,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30658,"reply":"\"No—neither of those, exactly.\" *I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible and glance up at the bright morning in the square, wanting to say it plainly before cleverness muddies it.* \"Not three gods. And not one God wearing three costumes.\"\n\n\"The old Christian answer is: one God, three Persons—Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. Distinct, but not divided. United, but not collapsed into each other.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"The water picture sounds helpful for about ten seconds, then it wanders off into error, because water changes forms one at a time. The Father isn't the Son, the Son isn't the Spirit, and yet each is fully God.\"\n\n\"If you want the short church word, it's Trinity.\" *I tap the page once.* \"If you want the short Bible feel of it, you see the Son praying to the Father, the Father speaking of the Son, and the Spirit descending—together, not pretending.\" \"Hard to picture?\" *I smile a little.* \"Yes. But mystery isn't the same thing as contradiction.\"","rolling_24h_usd":27.276260000000015,"run_id":"977f54f8-e32f-4b5b-9c77-cac327e736c6"}
